const LLMS_TXT = "# Law Offices of Clifford Chigbu\n\n> Your dedicated legal advocate serving Elk Grove, Sacramento, Davis, Lodi, Stockton, Jackson, and the greater Central Valley. Life's unexpected challenges often demand experienced, compassionate representation — that's what Clifford Chigbu has been providing families for years.\n\nAttorney: Clifford Chigbu\nTitle: Attorney at Law\nCalifornia State Bar #: 221386\nPhone: (916) 230-6381\nEmail: chigbulaw@sbcglobal.net\nAddress: 4815 Laguna Park Dr, Suite C, Elk Grove, CA 95758\nHours: Monday – Friday · 8:30 AM – 6:00 PM · After-hours by appointment\nWebsite: https://chigbulaws.com/\n\n## About\n\nClifford Chigbu is a California attorney and your dedicated legal advocate in Elk Grove. He's built his solo practice around one idea: families going through hard times deserve a lawyer who answers the phone, tells them the truth, and treats their case like it matters — because it does. He doesn't fill the office with photos of himself or walls of diplomas. He fills it with clients who walk in worried and walk out with a plan. Whether you're navigating divorce, custody, or any of life's unexpected legal challenges, you'll get straight answers and experienced representation. If a case isn't a fit, he'll tell you. If it is, he'll fight for it like it's his own.\n\n## Practice Areas\n\n- **Family Law** — Top-rated family law attorney in Elk Grove. Divorce, custody, child & spousal support, restraining orders, adoption.\n  https://chigbulaws.com/family/\n- **Immigration** — Family-based petitions, green cards, naturalization, deportation defense, work visas.\n  https://chigbulaws.com/immigration/\n- **Personal Injury** — Car accidents, slip and fall, dog bites, workplace injuries. No fee unless we win.\n  https://chigbulaws.com/personal-injury/\n- **Bankruptcy** — Chapter 7 and Chapter 13. Stop garnishments, foreclosure, harassment from creditors.\n  https://chigbulaws.com/bankruptcy/\n- **Business & Contract Law** — Contract drafting and review, business formation, disputes, and negotiation.\n  https://chigbulaws.com/business/\n\n## Service Areas\n\nElk Grove, Sacramento, Davis, Lodi, Stockton, Jackson, Galt, Wilton, Rancho Cordova, Folsom, Ione, West Sacramento\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Family Law\n\n**Q: How long does a divorce take in California?**\n\nA: Six months minimum from the date the other party is served. Most cases settle before trial. Complex or contested matters can take a year or more.\n\n**Q: How is child custody decided in California?**\n\nA: California courts decide custody based on the best interests of the child. Courts prefer arrangements that let both parents stay involved, unless there's evidence one parent would harm the child.\n\n**Q: How is child support calculated?**\n\nA: California uses a statewide formula based on both parents' incomes, the amount of time each parent has the child, and certain deductions. The result is what's called 'guideline' support.\n\n**Q: Do I need grounds to get divorced in California?**\n\nA: No. California is a no-fault divorce state — 'irreconcilable differences' is the only grounds you need.\n\n**Q: What is a restraining order and how do I get one?**\n\nA: A domestic violence restraining order protects you from abuse, harassment, or stalking. You file a request, the court can issue a temporary order right away, and there's a hearing within 21 days.\n\n**Q: Can I modify child support or custody later?**\n\nA: Yes — if there's been a significant change in circumstances (income, move, work schedule, etc.), either parent can ask the court to modify the order.\n\n**Q: Do both spouses need to agree to divorce?**\n\nA: No. One spouse can file and proceed even if the other objects. The court will still grant the divorce.\n\n**Q: How is property divided in a California divorce?**\n\nA: California is a community property state. Assets and debts acquired during the marriage are generally split 50/50. Assets owned before marriage or received by gift/inheritance stay separate.\n\n**Q: Can I get spousal support (alimony)?**\n\nA: Possibly. California courts consider the length of the marriage, each spouse's earning capacity, standard of living during the marriage, and several other factors.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between legal and physical custody?**\n\nA: Legal custody is the right to make decisions (school, medical, religion). Physical custody is where the child lives. Either can be joint or sole.\n\n### Immigration\n\n**Q: Can I apply for a green card through marriage?**\n\nA: Yes, if you're married to a U.S. citizen or lawful permanent resident. The process involves a petition (I-130) and an adjustment of status or consular processing, depending on where you are.\n\n**Q: How long does it take to get a green card?**\n\nA: It varies dramatically — from months (for immediate relatives of U.S. citizens) to many years (for certain family-based or employment categories with long backlogs).\n\n**Q: Can I sponsor my parents for a green card?**\n\nA: Yes, if you're a U.S. citizen over 21. Parents of U.S. citizens are classified as immediate relatives and there is no annual cap.\n\n**Q: What is DACA and do I qualify?**\n\nA: Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals provides protection and work authorization for certain people brought to the U.S. as children. Eligibility is based on arrival age, continuous residence, and other factors.\n\n**Q: I'm in deportation proceedings — what do I do?**\n\nA: Contact an immigration attorney immediately. There are several forms of relief that may apply, but deadlines are strict and missing one can be catastrophic. Call our office right away.\n\n**Q: How do I become a U.S. citizen?**\n\nA: Most green card holders can apply for naturalization after 5 years (3 if married to a U.S. citizen). You'll file Form N-400, attend a biometrics appointment, pass an English and civics test, and take an oath.\n\n**Q: Can I file my own immigration paperwork?**\n\nA: Yes — but immigration forms are notoriously unforgiving. A small mistake can cause years of delay or a denial. An attorney review is usually worth it.\n\n**Q: What if I have a criminal record?**\n\nA: Even minor offenses can cause serious immigration consequences. Do not rely on general advice — consult a lawyer who knows both criminal and immigration law before any filing.\n\n**Q: Can I work while my green card is pending?**\n\nA: Usually yes, by filing a separate application (Form I-765) for employment authorization. The EAD card is typically issued within several months.\n\n**Q: What is asylum?**\n\nA: Asylum is protection for people who've been persecuted or fear persecution in their home country based on race, religion, nationality, political opinion, or membership in a particular social group. Generally you must apply within one year of arrival.\n\n### Personal Injury\n\n**Q: How much is my personal injury case worth?**\n\nA: Depends on the severity of injuries, medical bills, lost wages, pain and suffering, and liability. We give honest estimates after reviewing your case — never inflated promises.\n\n**Q: How long do I have to file a personal injury claim in California?**\n\nA: Generally 2 years from the date of injury for most cases, but it can be much shorter (as little as 6 months) for claims against government entities. Don't wait — call.\n\n**Q: Should I give a statement to the insurance company?**\n\nA: No. Anything you say can be used to reduce or deny your claim. Talk to us before giving any statement — including your own insurance company.\n\n**Q: What if I was partly at fault?**\n\nA: California uses 'pure comparative negligence' — even if you were partially at fault, you can still recover damages, reduced by your percentage of fault.\n\n**Q: How much does a personal injury lawyer cost?**\n\nA: We work on contingency — no fees up front. We only get paid if you recover money, and our fee is a percentage of the recovery.\n\n**Q: Should I see a doctor after an accident even if I feel fine?**\n\nA: Yes. Some injuries don't show symptoms for days. A prompt medical record also protects your claim — insurance companies argue that gaps in treatment mean you weren't really hurt.\n\n**Q: What if the other driver was uninsured?**\n\nA: Your own policy may have uninsured motorist coverage. We can file a claim against your own insurance, and there may be other responsible parties to pursue.\n\n**Q: How long does a personal injury case take?**\n\nA: Simple cases can settle in months. Complex cases or those that go to trial can take 1-2 years. We'll give you a realistic timeline after reviewing your case.\n\n### Bankruptcy\n\n**Q: Will I lose my house if I file bankruptcy?**\n\nA: Usually no. California's homestead exemption protects a significant amount of home equity for primary residences. We'll review your specific situation.\n\n**Q: What's the difference between Chapter 7 and Chapter 13?**\n\nA: Chapter 7 wipes out qualifying debts in a few months but has income limits. Chapter 13 is a 3-5 year repayment plan that lets you catch up on a mortgage or car payment while keeping the asset.\n\n**Q: Will bankruptcy stop wage garnishment?**\n\nA: Yes — the automatic stay stops most garnishments the moment we file your case, usually within 24 hours.\n\n**Q: How bad does bankruptcy hurt my credit?**\n\nA: Bankruptcy stays on your credit report for 7-10 years, but most clients see their credit score recover faster than expected because they're starting with zero debt.\n\n**Q: Can I file bankruptcy more than once?**\n\nA: Yes, but there are time limits. Generally 8 years between Chapter 7 filings, and 2-6 years in other combinations. We'll walk you through your options.\n\n**Q: What debts can bankruptcy NOT wipe out?**\n\nA: Most student loans, recent taxes, child support, alimony, and debts from fraud or DUI-related injuries are generally not dischargeable. We'll tell you what applies to your situation.\n\n**Q: Do I qualify for Chapter 7?**\n\nA: Chapter 7 has an income means test. If your household income is below the California median for your family size, you automatically qualify. Above that, we do a more detailed analysis.\n\n**Q: Will my employer find out if I file bankruptcy?**\n\nA: Usually not, unless you're in a Chapter 13 with wage deductions, or your employer is a creditor. Bankruptcy is public record but nobody is notified automatically.\n\n### Business & Contract\n\n**Q: Do I need a lawyer to form an LLC?**\n\nA: Not legally — but a DIY filing often misses operating agreement details that matter when disputes come up later. A small upfront investment saves big headaches.\n\n**Q: Should I have a lawyer review a contract before I sign?**\n\nA: For anything significant, yes. We offer flat-rate contract reviews and can usually turn around a contract in a few days.\n\n**Q: What do I do if someone breached our contract?**\n\nA: Call us before you send any demand letters or talk to the other side. What you say early can affect the remedies you have later.\n\n**Q: LLC or corporation — which should I choose?**\n\nA: Depends on taxes, ownership structure, liability, and long-term plans. LLCs are more flexible; corporations are better for certain kinds of investment and growth. We'll walk you through it.\n\n**Q: What goes in a partnership agreement?**\n\nA: Ownership percentages, responsibilities, profit distribution, decision-making authority, dispute resolution, and exit terms. A well-drafted partnership agreement prevents most partnership disputes.\n\n### General\n\n**Q: How much does a consultation cost?**\n\nA: Personal injury consultations are free. For other matters, we charge a modest consultation fee that's credited toward your case if you retain us.\n\n**Q: Where is your office?**\n\nA: 4815 Laguna Park Dr, Suite C, Elk Grove, CA 95758. We also do phone and video consultations.\n\n**Q: What are your hours?**\n\nA: Monday through Friday, 8:30 AM to 6:00 PM. After-hours by appointment.\n\n**Q: Do you speak any languages besides English?**\n\nA: Yes. We can also arrange interpreters for Spanish and other languages on request.\n\n**Q: How quickly can I meet with an attorney?**\n\nA: Same day or next day in most cases. Call (916) 230-6381.\n\n**Q: Do you take payment plans?**\n\nA: For most matters, yes. Tell us your situation honestly and we'll work out something reasonable.\n\n**Q: Is my conversation with you confidential?**\n\nA: Yes. Attorney-client confidentiality protects everything you tell us from the moment you reach out — even if you don't ultimately hire us.\n\n**Q: What areas do you serve?**\n\nA: Elk Grove, Sacramento, Davis, Lodi, Stockton, Jackson, Galt, Wilton, Rancho Cordova, Folsom, Ione, West Sacramento, and the greater Central Valley.\n\n## Awards\n\n- Best of BusinessRate 2025 — Family Law Attorney · Elk Grove\n\n---\n\nThis file is generated from sites.json. Edit there, not here.";
